HashMap
=======

| Operation | Time |
| --------- | ---- |
| put       | O(1) |
| get       | O(1) |
| remove    | O(1) |

What is HashMap?
------------------
    HashMap is a data structure that implements the Map interface and stores key-value pairs using hashing
    It allows null keys and values, but only one null key
    It does not maintain any order of keys
    It is not synchronized, so it is not thread-safe
    It uses hash code of keys for fast access
    It allows duplicate values but not duplicate keys

What is Hashing?
------------------
    Hashing is a technique to convert a key into a number (index)

How HashMap Works:
------------------
                    Key → hashCode() → index → store value
HashMap converts a key into an index using hashCode and stores the value in that bucket

Example:
      "apple"
         ↓
      hashCode() → 93029210
         ↓
      index = 93029210 % 16 → 10
         ↓
      store at bucket[10]

Collision Handling
------------------
    When two keys hash to the same index, HashMap uses chaining (linked list or tree) to store multiple entries in the same bucket
    If bucket has multiple entries, it checks each entry for the key using equals() method
    If key found, update value; if not, add new entry to the bucket

Rehashing
-----------
When HashMap becomes too full, it expands:
    New array created (double size)
    All elements are rehashed
    Placed into new positions

Capacity = 16
Load factor = 0.75

Concurrent HashMap
------------------
    ConcurrentHashMap is a thread-safe variant of HashMap
    Segment locking / bucket-level locking allows concurrent access by multiple threads without full synchronization
    It does not allow null keys or values

| Structure         | Thread Safe? | Strategy        |
| ----------------- | ------------ | --------------- |
| HashMap           | ❌ No         | None            |
| Hashtable         | ✅ Yes        | Full locking    |
| ConcurrentHashMap | ✅ Yes        | Partial locking |



